===Etymology===
16th century, from {{bor|en|la|thēsaurus}}, from {{der|en|grc|θησαυρός||storehouse, treasure}}; its current English usage/meaning was established soon after the publication of Peter Roget's ''Thesaurus of English Words and Phrases'' in 1852

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/θɪˈsɔːɹəs/}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɔːɹəs}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|thesauri|thesauruses}}

# A [[publication]], usually in the form of a [[book]], that provides [[synonym]]s (and sometimes [[antonym]]s) for the [[word]]s of a given [[language]].
#: {{ux|en|"Roget" is the leading brand name for a print English '''thesaurus''' that lists words under general concepts rather than just close synonyms.}}
# {{lb|en|archaic}} A [[dictionary]] or [[encyclopedia]].
# {{lb|en|information science}} A [[hierarchy]] of [[subject]] [[heading]]s — [[canonic]] titles of [[theme]]s and [[topic]]s, the titles serving as search keys.

